<item>
            <title>[SPARK-25708] HAVING without GROUP BY means global aggregate</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-25708</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;According to the SQL standard, when a query contains `HAVING`, it indicates an aggregate operator. For more details please refer to &lt;a href=&quot;https://blog.jooq.org/2014/12/04/do-you-really-understand-sqls-group-by-and-having-clauses/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://blog.jooq.org/2014/12/04/do-you-really-understand-sqls-group-by-and-having-clauses/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, in Spark SQL parser, we treat HAVING as a normal filter when there is no GROUP BY, which breaks SQL semantic and lead to wrong result. This PR fixes the parser.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
